{"cursor":"87850","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Thermodynamic temperature' is the absolute measure of temperature and it is one\nof the principal parameters of thermodynamics.\n\nThermodynamic temperature is an \"absolute\" scale because it is the measure of\nthe fundamental property underlying temperature: its null or zero point,\nabsolute zero, is the temperature at which the particle constituents of matter\nhave minimal motion and can become no colder. Rankine, W.J.M., \"A manual of\nthe steam engine and other prime movers\", Richard Griffin and Co., London\n(1859), p. 306-7 Kelvin, \"Heat\", Adam and Charles Black, Edinburgh\n(1880), p. 39\n\nAt its simplest, temperature arises from the kinetic energy of the vibrational\nmotions of matter's particle constituents (molecules, atoms, and subatomic\nparticles). The full variety of these kinetic motions, along with potential\nenergies of particles, and also occasionally certain other types of particle\nenergy in equilibrium with these, contribute the total internal energy within a\nsubstance. Internal energy is loosely called the heat energy or thermal energy\nin conditions when no work is done upon the substance by its surroundings, or by\nthe substance upon the surroundings. Internal energy may be stored in a number\nof ways within a substance, but only the kinetic energy of particles contributes\nto the substance's temperature.\n","linknr":868,"url":"Absolute_temperature","recorded":1362372071,"links":64,"instances":["measure","astronomy","thermodynamics","chemistry","thermodynamics","unit","unit","mathematics","temperature","unit","physics","unit","physics_and_chemistry"],"pdf":["http://www.science.uva.nl/research/aplp/eprints/KasPhiRol95.pdf","http://www.whfreeman.com/college/pdfs/pchem8e/PC8eC21.pdf","http://theory.physics.helsinki.fi/~sol_phys/Sol0601.pdf","http://arxiv.org/pdf/astro-ph/0507099.pdf","http://iupac.org/publications/pac/2001/pdf/7308x1349.pdf","http://airmichelin.com/pdfs/05%20-%20Aircraft%20Tire%20Ratings.pdf","http://www.imeko.org/publications/tc12-2004/PTC12-2004-PL-001.pdf"],"categories":["Temperature","State functions"],"headings":["Overview","The relationship of temperature, motions, conduction, and heat energy","Practical applications for thermodynamic temperature","Definition of thermodynamic temperature","History","See also","Notes","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/22/Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg/220px-Carnot_heat_engine_2.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/4/354c808b3ac7ff5bd75faa26bcc36220.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/9/e/b9ece18c950afbfa6b0fdbfa4ff731d3.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/e/7/de71b72c4f62f20d117414dd2f33ca25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/d/9/8d9c307cb7f3c4a32822a51922d1ceaa.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/a/e/2aede3b55c027fe4392429d6474ec397.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/c/c4ca4238a0b923820dcc509a6f75849b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/8/888fa252e9cde41ef196d5154cd7219c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/f/5/1f58273c4161e57f62a95804c2ae961a.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/7/e/17eb927e31859ce116f5c64cbcc30d75.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/c/c4ca4238a0b923820dcc509a6f75849b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/8/8/888fa252e9cde41ef196d5154cd7219c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5206560a306a2e085a437fd258eb57ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/f/7/af7e8a85df47250ffab736b7a8807488.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/1/5/8153e779d69fe6c35dc2bc4dfb0f2a11.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/7/5/5758e3126ffd73977ec11d0c19d06692.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/6/7/5678e99000d8069acd323bb63d6376d4.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/0/5205e29e7201a0b009466036b40a34a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6d/Translational_motion.gif","//bits.wikimedia.or